Section 1: Working with Pandas¶

For this section, we will use the files in the folder named gapminder that is inside the data folder. These files contain the per capita GDP for countries within various regions of the world. The file name indicates which region the data belongs to.

Within each section the questions guide you to a final analysis. You should not re-import the data unless intructed.

Q1) Import the files.¶

Import the files gapminder_gdp_americas.csv and gapminder_gdp_europe.csv and save them into dataframes named americas_df and europe_df respectively. In both dataframes, make country the index. Make sure that you use relative paths.

folder_path = 'data/gapminder/' #rel path
region_df = pd.DataFrame() #empty df

for filename in os.listdir(folder_path):
    if filename.endswith('.csv'):
        region = os.path.splitext(filename)[0].split('_')[2] # Extract the region/continent from the filename
        
        file_path = os.path.join(folder_path, filename) #full file path
        
        # Read the CSV file and append it to the region_df DataFrame
        df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
        df['Region'] = region  # Add Region column with the region/continent name
        region_df = pd.concat([region_df, df], ignore_index=True)

Section 2: Capital Bikeshare Rides and Weather¶

Capital Bikeshare Data: In the captialbikeshare folder. https://capitalbikeshare.com/system-data

Data Description:

  • Duration – Duration of trip
  • Start Date – Includes start date and time
  • End Date – Includes end date and time
  • Start Station – Includes starting station name and number
  • End Station – Includes ending station name and number
  • Bike Number – Includes ID number of bike used for the trip
  • Member Type – Indicates whether user was a "registered" member (Annual Member, 30-Day Member or Day Key Member) or a "casual" rider (Single Trip, 24-Hour Pass, 3-Day Pass)

Weather Data: arboretum_weather_2022.csv (Climate Data Online: https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/cdo-web/)

Data Description:

  • DAPR - Number of days included in the multiday precipitation total (MDPR)
  • SNOW - Snowfall
  • WT11 - High or damaging winds
  • WT01 - Fog, ice fog, or freezing fog (may include heavy fog)
  • TMAX - Maximum temperature
  • WESD - Water equivalent of snow on the ground
  • TMIN - Minimum temperature
  • PRCP - Precipitation
  • TOBS - Temperature at the time of observation
  • MDPR - Multiday precipitation total (use with DAPR and DWPR, if available)
  • SNWD - Snow depth

Goal of Analysis¶

The analytical goal of this section is to be able to predict the number of daily rides based on the weather.

Q13) Import the Capital Bikeshare Data¶

Inside the data/capitalbikeshare/ folder there are 3 data files. Import them into a single dataframe named bikeshare_df. Make sure that you use relative paths and that you use a loop to import the files. You should not have to hard code any file names.

import os
path = 'data/capitalbikeshare/'
files = []

for filename in os.listdir(path):
    if filename.endswith('.csv'):
        filepath = os.path.join(path, filename)
        
        # Read the CSV file into df
        bike_dfs = pd.read_csv(filepath)
        
        # Append the dataframe to the list
        files.append(bike_dfs)
        
        #concat dfs into dataframe
        bikeshare_df = pd.concat(files)

def timedelta_to_minutes(td):
    return td.total_seconds() / 60 #convert to seconds, divide by 60; 60 secs = 1 min

We only need the values in the following columns:

  • TMAX: Maximum temperature
  • TMIN: Minimum temperature
  • PRCP: Amount of precipitation (in inches)

Explain your answer in the markdown cell below and in the code cell write the code to implement your method.

Since this dataset is a time series of weather data for the entire year of 2022 and we can assume the missing values are of MCAR type-- we could use interpolation to handle the missing values for our specified columns. Interpolation uses data patterns in time series data, and provides accurate estimates based on neighboring values.

Q20) Data Integration and Data Fusion¶

You should have noticed that the two datasets are at different levels of analysis. The rides data is at the level of individual rides while the weather data is at the daily level. In order to merge the two datasets, we will need to get them to be at the same level of analysis.

Is this considered data integration or data fusion? Explain your answer.

Use the markdown cell below to answer this question.

The merge of bikeshare data and weather data could be classified as data fusion. In this situation, we could merge the bikeshare data and weather data to gain insights on whether weather has an impact on bike rides such as ride time spent (duration of ride), ride distance, common start or end stations, frequency of bike rides in the day and more. Essentially, this type of analysis wouldn't be possible alone without the combination of these two datasets that actually appear to have a correlation when combined.

The results displayed by the correlation and scatterplot tests between number of rides and the weather variables, there seems to be a very weak correlation between weather and number of rides. Precipitation has a correlation coefficient of is -0.013955, suggesting a very weak negative relationship. This implies that there is almost no association between precipitation and the number of rides. Rainy days are not significantly impacting the ridership patterns. Maximum temperature has a correlation coefficient of 0.216630, indicating a moderate negative relationship. This suggests that higher maximum temperatures may be associated with a slight decrease in the number of rides. Lastly, minimum temperature has a correlation coefficient of -0.338678, suggesting a moderate negative relationship. This indicates that lower minimum temperatures are associated with a moderate decrease in the number of rides.

In conclusion, there seems to be a negatively weak to moderate relationship between number of rides and the weather variables. In actuality, I could see how weather may impact the number of rides taken in a day. It would be logical if there was an increase in bikeshare use during warmer weather and climates versus colder ones. In addition, I could see how weather like rain or snow could reduce the likelihood of using bikeshare services and even significantly decrease the duration of trips. Unfortunately, this is analysis I hoped to represent in my models, however, the dataframes were limited and more variables and factors would have to be involved.
